{"/service/ndnp/mnhi/batch_mnhi_caesar_ver01/data/sn91059411/00517011769/1930073101/0270.xml":{"full_text":"PAGE SIX\nTHE TOWN DOCTOR\n\u201cDoctor of Towns\u201d\n4 SATS\nBUSINESS DEPRESSION IS\nLARGELY A STATE OF MIND\nThere have been given a thousand\none reasons by as many experts for\nthe recent falling off of business.\nTwice as many articles have been\nwritten and published expounding\nand giving \u201creasons why\u201d for this\nbusiness depression, and easily three\ntimes as many speeches and talks\nhave been made before business or\nganizations explaining cause and ef\nfect. All of these opinions admit and\nagree that there is a depression.\nIn the face of, and irrespective of\nall this, I make so bold as to say that\nall so-called \u201clack of business,\u201d this\nadmitted \u201cbusiness depression\u201d is 90\npercent mental; and that the elimina\ntion of the hazard lies in proving\nthat it is mental, which requires\nnothing more than selling \u2014\u201c1930\nSelling.\u201d Not selling as it is popular\nly construed and thought of; not just\nthe motions of one person making\ntransfer of ownership of a product,\nservice or thing, in exchange for a\nconsideration; but \u201c1930 Influenc\ning\u201d\nThere is no intent to make denial\nof the fact that as a whole the con\nsumer is not consuming as he once\ndid; that business is not as good as\nit once was. But the fault lies, not\nwith \u201cbusiness,\u201d but with the people\nwho are in business and those with\nwhom they do business.\nNinety-nine and a fraction percent\nof all of us are naturally and in\nstinctively lazy, especially when it\ncomes to continued physical exertion,\nand more especially when it comes\nto that exercise commonly known as\n\u201cthinking.\u201d We are constantly look\ning for an alibi to \u201clet down\u201d and\nan excuse to worry, which in itself is\nan alibi for failure to do real con\nstructive thinking.\nWe are not only lazy by nature,\nwe are all more or less cowards \u2014a\nbunch of scaredy cats, afraid to dis\nagree with the crowd \u2014one reason for\nwhich is that to be different requires\nbrain work.\nMany who read this will say, \u201cThis\nfellow is crazy. He don\u2019t know what\nhe is talking about. The idea of say\ning this depression which is as plain\nas day\u2014which everyone knows as an\nexisting condition \u2014is a myth!\u201d\nOthers will say: \u201cYou can\u2019t tell me\nthat I merely \u2018imagine\u201d that business\nis not what it used to be, when I see\nit every day, right before my eyes.\u201d\nWell it is often the case that to\nmany, what is, isn\u2019t at all. Often that\nwhich seems to be, is not a reality\nexcept to those who refuse to look\nfor reality. Many a mirage is more\nplain than the real. You can\u2019t make\na crazy man believe you are Napol\neon if he thinks he is.\nThis picture, which so many peo\nple have of business, is a mirage; but\nit might as well be a fact and the\nreal thing, and it will be just that,\nas long as they refuse to look at any\nthing but the mirage.\nThere is just as much business as\nthere ever was. And there is just as\nmuch money as there ever was, too.\nYou haven\u2019t heard of any catastro\nphe that has destroyed or obliterated\nthe coin of the realm, have you? You\nhaven\u2019t read of any of the country\u2019s\nmoney being burned up, and certainly\nthe people of these United States\nhaven\u2019t reverted to the customs and\nways of doing things of those of the\nStone Age. As long as there is mon\ney and people there IS plenty of busi\nness.\nThis lack of business is all in our\nheads. It started in the head, contin\nues in the head, and in the head lies\nthe ending of it.\n(Copyright, 1930, A. D. Stone. Re\nproduction prohibited in whole or in\npart. This editorial published by The\nTimes in co-operation with Mora\nLions Club.)\nOGILVIE NEWS\n(From the Sentinel)\nA. E. Hawk\u2019s name was broadcast\ned over WCCO the past week as one\nof the winners of an ash tray given\naway by the Worch Cigar Company,\nof St. Paul. Newton Conger was also\na winner of a tray.\nJohn Bystrom, who has been in\nvery poor health of late, was taken\nto the Braham hospital Sunday and\non Monday was taken to the Univer\nsity hospital. He has a throat afflic\ntion, but at this writing was reported\nas being somewhat better.\nJos. Folsom was taken to the\nNorthwestern hospital at Princeton\nlast Friday afternoon, where he un\nderwent an operation for appendici\ntis the same afternoon. He is getting\nalong very nicely. His brother, Ches\nter, is taking his place at the G. 17.\nstation.\nJohn Bolte is at the Northwestern\nhospital at Princeton, where he will\nundergo an operation for gland\ntrouble as soon as he regains suffi\ncient strength, which is expected will\nbe some time this week. Since put\nting the above in type we have been\ninformed that Mr. Bolte underwent\nthe operation on Tuesday.\nChas. Thornton, who has been\nworking in Des Moines, commenced\nwork for the E. A. Porter garage\nMonday. Charley is an experienced\nmechanic and knows the business.\nHe and Arthur will make a good com\nbination and automobile owners know\nthat their cars will be taken care of\nby men of experience and ability.\u2014\nAltoona, lowa, Herald.\nMrs. Sanders has sold her restaur\nant to Miss Marion Forbish. Miss\nForbish, who has been operator at\nthe Ogilvie telephone office for\nmany years, has resigned her posi\ntion and will take charge of her new\nbusiness enterprise on Friday of this\nweek. Mrs. Sanders and son expect\nto leave this week for their farm\nnear Jacobson, Minn., where they will\nbe indefinitely located.\nRead the Times for interesting\nnews of your community and county.\nLAST BANQUET OF\nLAST MAN\u2019S CLUB\nStillwater Gazette, July 24.\u2014The\nfaint scent of red, white and blue\ngarden flowers diffused from bou\nquets at 33 crepe draped places Mon\nday afternoon as Charles Lockwood\nsaid goodbye to his comrades of\nbattle.\nLockwood kept a promise made 45\nyears ago.\nHe sipped a toast to the memory\nof his dead comrades and he closed\nthe records of the Last Man\u2019s Club,\nfamous organization of Company B,\nFirst Minnesota Volunteer Infantry.\nIt was America\u2019s strangest ban\nquet.\nThere were 33 vacant chairs at the\nbanquet table. Each chair was drap\ned in crepe, with the crepe tied in a\nwhite ribbon on which had been\nwritten the name of the departed\ncomrade.\nWith Lockwood at the banquet\ntable sat Mrs. Helen McCluer of\nStillwater, president of the Stillwat\ner Public Library board, who was\npresented the bottle of wine for safe\nkeeping in the library, Mrs. Nellie\nBloomer, widow of the late Samuel\nBloomer, a member of the club, and\nL. S. Staples, secretary of the Min\nnesota Territorial Pioneer\u2019s associa\ntion.\nMemories carried Lockw\u2019ood away\nas he recited:\n\u201cThe campfire smoulders \u2014ashes\nfall;\nThe clouds are black against the\nsky;\nNo tap of drums, no bugle call;\nMy comrades all goodbye.\u201d\nWhile the lone survivor made this\ntoast to the dead, talking cameras\nrecorded for all time the termina\ntion of the only club of its kind in\nthe world.\nSpectators crowded the hall and\nat other tables -were seated members\nof the G. A. R., old pioneers of this\ncommuninty, Minnesota territorial\npioneers, and others.\nThe main banquet was beautifully\ndecorated with cut flowers. On the\nwall to the rear was the framed flag\nof the company, while on one side\nwere the colors of the American Le\ngion and Veterans of the Foreign\nWars and on the other side two U.\nS. colors. A squad of Co. A, Nation\nal Guard of Stillwater, stood guard\nat the main banquet table and their\nkhaki uniforms added to the colorful\nscene.\nOn the banquet table was the bou\nquet from Mrs. Helen McCluer. At\neach banquet of the club there has\nbeen a similar bouquet. Judge Wil\nliam McCluer, her husband, had\npledged at the time the club was\nformed to see to it that the \u201cboys\u201d\nhad a bouquet of flowers at each of\nthe banquets and when he died his\nwidow took up the task and has nev\ner failed.\nAlso at the banquet table were\nbouquets from Mrs. Helen Torinus\nand from the \u201cShepard girls,\u201d daugh\nters of the late Myron Shepard, who\nwas a member of the club.\nLockwood was brought to Still\nwater Sunday afternoon by Lloyd\nKoiliner, commander of the Stillwat\ner American Legion, in his automo\nbile. Lockwood remained at the Low\nell Inn during the night and Monday\nmorning he was up bright and early,\nready to carry out his \u201ctryst with\nthe dead.\u201d\nMrs. Nellie Bloomer was also ear\nly at the scene of the banquet and\naided in decorating the table and see\ning to it that everything was like\nthe \u201cboys\u201d would have wanted it.\nThe banquet began shortly after\none o\u2019clock in the afternoon and af\nter the dinner, the final ceremonies\nof the club were held.\nWalter Prince of the First National\nBank presented the bottle of wine to\nMr. Lockwood and Mr. Staples read\nthe roll. Silence greeted the names\nof 33 of the veterans and Lockwood\nbowed his head. As the 34th name\nwas called \u201cLockwood,\u201d the sole sur\nvivor, got to his feet and in a clear\nvoice said \u201cPresent.\u201d\nHe then read the final stanzas of\nHayden\u2019s poem \u201cThe Last Survivor\u201d\nand drank a toast in clear water. The\nwine, which had been opened some\nyears ago and which at that time\nwas found to have turned to vinegar,\nwas untouched.\nLockwood then presented the bottle\nof wine to Mrs. McCluer for keeping\nat the Stillwater public library.\nMayor Sniels presented the surviv\nor with the resolution of congratula\ntions passed by the city council and\nurged that Lockwood return to Still\nwater each year and continue to hold\nhis \u201creunions.\u201d\n\u201cMany thanks to my very kind\nfriends in Stillwater,\u201d answered the\nold soldier.\n\u201cMany thanks. I don\u2019t feel as if I\ncan talk much but I thank you all.\u201d\nThe banquet was over. The pledge\nhad been kept. The club\u2019s records\nhad been closed.\nBlow, Boys, Blow!\n\u201c.The best thing for you would be\na sea voyage. Can you manage it?\u201d\n\u201cI think so, doctor, I am captain\nof a trans-Atlantic liner.\u201d\u2014Buen\nHumor.\n(July 17-24-31)\nnotice of\nSALE OF FORFEITED LAND\nNOTICE IS HEREBY GIVEN that,\nbeginning on the second Monday in\nAugust, 1930, at ten o\u2019clock A. M. and\ncontinuing from day to day thereafter\nuntil the first day of Septmeber and\nthereafter on the second Monday of\nSeptember and on the second Monday of\neach month thereafter until and includ\ning the second Monday of December of\nthe same year, at which time the sale\nwill be completed, I will offer for sale\nto the highest cash bidder therefor, at\nthe office of the County Auditor at\nMora, in the County of Kanabec, Min\nnesota, pursuant to the provisions of\nGeneral Statutes 1923, Sections 2138\nand 2139 as amended, all parcels of\nland bid in for the State and not as\nsigned to purchasers or redeemed with\nin three years from the date of the\ntax sale at which they were offered.\nThe rights of the state acquired at\ndelinquent tax sales in the year 1928\nand subsequent years, and the Hens for\nsubsequent delinquent taxes attaching\nthereto, will not be disposed of at this\nsale.\nDated at Mora, Minnesota, this 16th\nday of July, 1930.\nG. G. BILLSTROM,\nCounty Auditor of Kanabec\nCounty, Minn.\nKANABEC COUNTY TIMES, MORA, MINNESOTA.\nFreedom from gangs is much like\nother freedom. It is reserved for\nthose who have backbone enough to\nwin it.\u2014Springfield News-Sun.\n(July 17-24-31)\nG TIME TO FILE\nCLAIMS AND FOB HEARING\nTHEREON\nORDER\nState of Minnesota)\n)ss. In Probate Court\nCounty of Kanabec)\nIn the Matter of the Estate\nof Frank Belkholm, Deced\nent.\nLetters of administration this day\nhaving been granted to Joseph T. Belk\nholm.\nIT IS ORDERED, That the time\nwithin which all creditors of the above\nnamed decedent may present claims\nagainst his estate in this Court, be, and\nthe same hereby is, limited to Six\nmonths from and after the date here\nof; and that February 2nd, 1931, at 10\no\u2019clock A. M., in the Probate Court\nRooms at the Court House at Mora,\nin said County, be, and the same here\nby is, fixed and appointed as the time\nand place for hearing upon and the\nexamination, adjustment and allowance\nof such claims as shall be presented\nwithin the time aforesaid.\nLet notice hereof be given by the\npublication of this order in the Kana\nbec County Times as provided by law,\nand by mailed notice as provided by\nthe rules of this court.\nDated July Bth, 1930.\nADOLPH S. OLSON,\n(Court Seal) Judge of Probate.\n(July 24-31-Aug. If\nCITATION FOR HEARING ON PETI\nTION FOR ADMINISTRATION\nState of Minnesota)\n\nCounty of Kanabec)\nIn Probate Court\nIn the Matter of the Estate of F. T.\nKettelhodt, Decedent.\nTHE STATE OF MINNESOTA TO\nall persons interested in the granting\nof Administration of the estate of said\ndecedent. The petition of Elvena E.\nKettelhodt having been filed in this\ncourt, representing that F. T. Kettel\nhodt, then a resident of the County of\nKanabec, State of Minnesota, died in\ntestate on the 19th day of July, 1930;\nand praying that letters of Administra\ntion of his estate be granted to Elvena\nE. Kettelhodt; and the court, having\nfixed the time and place for hearing\nsaid petition.\nTherefore, YOU, AND EACH OF\nYOU, are hereby cited and required to\nshow cause, if any you have, before\nthis Court at the Probate Court Rooms\nin the Court House, in the Village of\nMora, in the County of Kanabec, State\nof Minnesota, on the 18th day of Aug\nust, 1930, at 10 o\u2019clock A. M., why said\npetition should not be granted.\nWITNESS, the Judge of said Court,\nand Seal of said Court, this 22nd day\nof July, 1930.\nADOLPH S. OLSON,\n(Court Seal) Judge of Probate Court.\nJ. C. POPE,\nAttorney for Petitioner.\n(July 24-31-Aug. 7)\nNOTICE OF EXFIBATION OF TIME\nOF BEDEMFTION\nOffice of County Auditor)\nCounty of Kanabec )ss.\nState of Minnesota\nTO WM. A. DAY,\n(1) You are hereby notified that the\nfollowing piece or parcel of land situ\nated in the County of Kanabec, State\nof Minnesota, and known and described\nas follows, to-wit:\nLot No. 2, Block No. 14, Lake\nPark Addition, to the Village of\nMora,\nIS NOW ASSESSED IN YOUR NAME.\n(2) That on the 9th day of May,\n1910, at a sale of land pursuant to the\nreal estate tax judgment duly given\nand made in and by the District Court\nin said County of Kanabec, on the 30th\nday of March, 1910, in proceedings to\nenforce the payment of taxes delin\nquent upon real estate for the year\n1908, for said County of Kanabec, the\nabove described piece or parcel of land\nwas offered for sale, and no one bid\nding upon said offer, said piece or par\ncel, was bid in for the State of Minne\nsota for the sum of 61/100), Only\n61/100 Dollars.\n(3) That thereafter, and on the 9th\nday of December, 1929, the said piece\nor parcel not then having been re\ndeemed from said sale, was sold and\nconveyed at public sale by the County\nAuditor of said County, pursuant to\nthe statute, to an actual purchaser for\nthe sum of Two Dollars and Nine cents.\n(4) That the amount required to re\ndeem said piece or parcel of land from\nsaid sale, exclusive of the costs to ac\ncrue upon this notice, is the sum of\n($2.09), Two Dollars and Nine cents,\nand interest at the rate of 12 per cent\nper annum on ($2.09), Two 09/100\nDollars from said 9th day of December,\n1929, to the day such redemption is\nmade.\n(5) That the tax certificate of sale\nissued to said purchaser has been pre\nsented to me by the holder thereof and\nthis notice requested.\n(6) That the time for the redemp\ntion of said piece or parcel of land from\nsaid tax sale will expire sixty (60)\ndays after the service of this notice,\nand the filing of proof of such service\nin my office.\nWITNESS my hand and official seal\nthis 11th day of February, 1930.\nG. G. BILLSTROM,\n(Official Auditor, Kanabec County,\nSeal) Minnesota.\n(July 24-31-Aug. 7)\nNOTICE OF EXPIRATION OF TIME\nOF REDEMPTION\nOffice of County Auditor)\nCounty of Kanabec )ss.\nState of Minnesota\nTO WM. A. DAY,\n(1) You are hereby notified that the\nfollowing piece or parcel of land situ\nated in the County of Kanabec, State\nof Minnesota, and known and described\nas follows, to-wit:\nLot No. 1, Block No. 14, Lake\nPark Addition, to the Village of\nMora,\nIS NOW ASSESSED IN YOUR NAME.\n(2) That on the 9th day of May,\n1910, at a sale of land pursuant to the\nreal estate tax judgment duly given and\nmade in and by the District Court in\nsaid County of Kanabec on the 30th day\nof March, 1910, in proceedings to en\nforce the payment of taxes delinquent\nupon real estate for the year 1908, for\nsaid County of Kanabec, the above de\nscribed piece or parcel of land was of\nfered for sale, and no one bidding upon\nsaid offer, said piece or parcel, was bid\nin for the State of Minnesota for the\nsum of 61/100), Only 61/100 Dol\nlars.\n(3) That thereafter, and on the 9th\nday of December, 1929, the said piece\nor parcel not then having been re\ndeemed from said sale, was sold and\nconveyed at public sale by the County\nAuditor of said County, pursuant to\nthe statute, to an actual purchaser for\nthe sum of Two Dollars and Thirty-\nSix cents.\n(4) That the amount required to re\ndeem said piece or parcel of land from\nsaid sale, exclusive of the costs to ac\ncrue upon this notice, is the sum of\n($2.36), Two Dollars and Thirty-Six\ncents, and interest at the rate of 12\nper cent per annum on ($2.36), Two\n36/100 Dollars from said 9th day of\nDecember, 1929, to the day such re\ndemption is made.\n(5) That the tax certificate of sale\nissued to said purchaser has been pre\nsented to me by the holder thereof and\nthis notice requested.\n(6) That the time for the redemp\ntion of said piece or parcel of land\nfrom said tax sale will expire sixty\n(60) days after the service of this no\ntice, and the filing of proof of such\nservice in my office.\nWITNESS my hand and official seal\nthis 11th day of February, 1930.\nG. G. BILLSTROM,\n(Official Auditor, Kanabec County,\nSeal) Minnesota.\n(July 31-Aug. 7-14)\nCITATION FOB HEARING ON FINAL\nACCOUNT AND FOB\nDISTBXBUTION\nState of Minnesota)\n)ss. In Probate Court\nCounty of Kanabec)\nIn the Matter of the Estate of\nGustaf Emil Erickson, also\ndesignated as Gustav E. Er-\nickson, Deceased.\nTHE STATE OF MINNESOTA TO ALL\nWHOM IT MAY CONCERN:\nOn reading and filing the petition of\nthe representative of the said estate,\npraying that the Court fix a time and\nplace for examining, adjusting and al\nlowing his FINAL ACCOUNT, and for\nthe assignment of the residue of said\nestate, being the proceeds of War Risk\nInsurance, to the persons thereto en\ntitled,\nIT IS ORDERED, That said petition\nbe heard and that all persons inter\nested in said matter be cited and re\nquired to appear before this Court, on\nTuesday, the 26th day of August, 1930,\nat two o\u2019clock in the afternoon, or as\nsoon thereafter as said matter can be\nheard, at the Probate Court Room, in\nthe Court House, in the Village of\nMora, in said County, and show cause,\nif any they have, why said petition\nshould not be granted, and that this ci\ntation be served by publication thereof\nin the Kanabec County Times according\nto law 7\nWITNESS the Judge of said Court\n^this 25th day of July, 1930.\nADOLPH S. OLSON,\nJudge of Probate Court.\nI (Seal of the Probate Court)\nJ. A. JACKSON,\nAttorney,\n401 New York Building,\nSt. Paul, Minnesota.\n(July 17-24-31-Aug. 7-14-21)\nNOTICE OF\nMOBTGAGE FOBECLOSUBE SALE,\nDefault having been made in the con\nditions of that certain mortgage dated\nthe 27th day of September, 1926, exe\ncuted by Theodore Randall and Louise\nO. Randall, his wife, to the First Na\ntional Bank of Mora, Minnesota, (a\nCorporation), and filed in the office of\nthe Register of Deeds of Kanabec\nCounty, Minnesota, on the 27th day of\nSeptember, 1926, and then and there re\ncorded in Book Number five of Mort\ngages, on page 346, which said mort\ngage was duly assigned by the First\nNational Bank of Mora, Minnesota, by\nwritten assignment to S. D. Mcllhar\ngey, dated the twenty-third day of\nJune, 1930, which assignment was re\ncorded in the office of the Register of\nDeeds of Kanabec County, Minnesota,\non the 24th day of June, 1930, at 3\no\u2019clock P. M. in Book Number ten of\nmortgages on page 59, that the prem\nises described and covered by said\nmortgage are in Kanabec County, Min\nnesota, to-wit:\nThe North Half of the North-\nWest Quarter (N% of NW%) of\nSection thirty-four (34), Township\nForty-two (42), Range Twenty\nthree (23), containing eighty acres\nmore or less,\nOn which mortgage there is due and\nclaimed to be due at the date hereof\nthe sum of One Thousand Eight Hund\nred Sixty and 26/100 Dollars, ($1860.26)\nitemized as follows:\nBalance principal declared\ndue $1,500.00\nInterest Coupon due Nov. Ist,\n1927 90.00\nAccrued interest from Nov.\nIst, 1927 to July 10th, 1930 14.57\nInterest Coupon due Nov. Ist,\nfrom Nov.\n1928\nAccrued interest\nIst, 1928 to July 10th, 1930 9.17\nInterest Coupon due Nov. Ist,\n1929 90.00\nAccrued interest from Nov.\nIst, 1929 to July 10th, 1930 3.77\nAccrued interest on principal\nfrom Nov. Ist, 1929 to July\n10th, 1930 62.75\nAnd Whereas no action at law or\notherwise having been begun to recover\nsaid sum or any part thereof.\nNow, Therefore, Notice is hereby\ngiven that by virtue of the power of\nsale in said mortgage contained, said\nmortgage will be foreclosed by the sale\nof the above described premises to the\nhighest bidder by the Sheriff of said\nKanabec County, at the front door of\nthe Court House, in the Village of\nMora, Minnesota, on Saturday, the 30th\nday of August, 1930, at ten o\u2019clock A.\nM. to satisfy the sum then due on the\nprincipal of said mortgage with inter\nest, and the taxes, if any on said\npremises and the sum of Seventy-five\nDollars attorneys fees, as stipulated in\nsaid Mortgage, and the disbursements\nallowed by law.\nDated July 10th, 1930.\nS. D. McILHARGEY,\nAssignee of Mortgagee.\nJ. C. POPE,\nAttorney for Mortgagee,\nMora, Minnesota.\n(July 10-17-24-31-Aug. 7-14)\nNOTICE OF BEAL ESTATE MORT\nGAGE FORECLOSURE SALE.\nNotice is hereby given that default\nhas been made in the conditions of that\ncertain mortgage dated October sth,\n1923, executed by Nettie B. Hill and\nClarence O. Hill, her husband, as mort\ngagors, to the State of Minnesota, as\nmortgagee, filed for record in the office\nof the Register of Deeds in and for Ka\nnabec County, State of Minnesota, on\nOctober 6th, 1923, at four o\u2019clock P. M.,\nand duly recorded in Book \u201cV\u201d of\nMortgages, on pages 383 and 384 there\nof; that default consists in the failure\nto pay the semi-annual Installments of\namortized principal and interest for\n$203.13 each, due on October sth, 1929,\nand April sth, 1930, respectively; and\nto pay the taxes on the hereinafter de\nscribed mortgaged premises; that un\nder the terms thereof there is actually\ndue and claimed to be due on said mort\ngage, at the date hereof, the sum of\n$6,004.06, unamortized principal, togeth\ner with interest thereon from April sth,\n1930, at the rate of five and one-fourth\nper cent, per annum, the sum of\n$406.26, amortized principal and inter\nest, with interest on $203.13 thereof\nsince October sth, 1929, and on $203.13\nthereof since April sth, 1930, each at\nthe rate of seven per cent, per annum,\nand the sum of $55.36 for taxes, includ\ning interest, penalties and costs, and\ninterest thereon at the rate of seven per\ncent, per annum to the date hereof, in\nall the sum of $6,562.52, Including in\nterest on said respective sums from\nsaid respective dates and at the respec\ntive rates as aforesaid; that no action\nor proceeding at law or otherwise has\nbeen instituted to recover the debt se\ncured by said mortgage, or any part\nthereof; that pursuant to the power of\nsale in said mortgage contained, said\nmortgage will be foreclosed and the\nlands and premises therein described,\nlying and being in Kanabec County,\nMinnesota, to-wit:\nThe Southeast Quarter (SE^i) of\nSection Thirty-four (34), in Township\nForty (40), of Range Twenty-five (25),\ncontaining 160 acres, more or less, ac\ncording to the Government survey\nthereof, with the hereditaments and ap\npurtenances, will be sold by the Sheriff\nof said Kanabec County, at the front\ndoor of the Court House, in the Village\nof Mora, in said County and State, on\nFriday, the 22nd day of August, 1930,\nat ten o\u2019clock in the forenoon of that\nday, at public vendue to the highest\nbidder for cash, to pay and satisfy the\ndebt then due on said mortgage, includ\ning said taxes paid, as aforesaid, and\nthe taxes, if any, on said premises, and\nthe costs and disbursements allowed by\nlaw, subject to redemption at any time\nwithin one year from the date of sale,\nas provided by law.\nDated July 9th, 1930.\nSTATE OF MINNESOTA, Mortgagee,\nBy Department of Rural Credit.\nOLE O. SAGENG, Chairman.\nAttest: H. H. FLOWERS, Secretary.\n(Department Seal)\nHENRY N. BENSON, Attorney General.\nH. M. FEROE, Ass\u2019t. Attorney General.\nAttorneys for Mortgagee,\n610 Hamm Building,\nSt. Paul, Minnesota.\nA Pint of Accuracy\nTwo Scotsmen had not encountered\neach other for 20 years.\n\u201cWell, well, well,\u201d said one, \u201cthis\nis an historic occasion. We\u2019ll have\nto wet it.\u201d\n\u201cAye,\u201d agreed the other, \u201cso we\nwill. But ye\u2019ll forgive me for remind\nin\u2019 ye that I paid the last time.\u201d\n(July 24-31-Aug. 7)\nNOTICE OF EXFIBATION- OF TIME\nOF BEDEMPTION\nOffice of County Auditor)\nCounty of Kanabec )ss.\nState of Minnesota\nTO WM. A. DAY,\n(1) You are hereby notified that the\nfollowing piece or parcel of land situ\nated in the County of Kanabec, State\nof Minnesota, and known and described\nas follows, to-wit:\nLot No. 4, Block No. 14, Lake\nPark Addition, to the Village of\nMora,\nIS NOW ASSESSED IN YOUR NAME.\n(2) That on the 9th day of May,\n1910, at a sale of land pursuant to the\nreal estate tax judgment duly given\nand made in and by the District Court\nin said County of Kanabec on the 30th\nday of March, 1910, in proceedings to\nenforce the payment of taxes delin\nquent upon real estate for the year\n1908, for said County of Kanabec, the\nabove described piece or parcel of\nland was offered for sale, and no one\nbidding upon said offer, said piece or\nparcel w 7 as bid in for the State of Min\nnesota for the sum of 61/100), Only\n61/100 Dollars.\n(3) That thereafter, and on the 9th\nday of December, 1929, the said piece\nor parcel not then having been redeem\ned from said sale, was sold and con\nveyed at public sale by the County Au\nditor of said County, pursuant to the\nstatute, to an actual purchaser for the\nsum of One Dollar and Six cents.\n(4) That the amount required to re\ndeem said piece or parcel of land from\nsaid sale, exclusive of the costs to ac\ncrue upon this notice, is the sum of\n($1.06), One Dollar and Six cents, and\ninterest at the rate of 12 per cent per\nannum on ($1.06), One 06/100 Dol\nlars from said 9th day of December,\n1929, to the day such redemption is\nmade.\n(5) That the tax certificate of sale\nissued to said purchaser has been pre\nsented to me by the holder thereof and\nthis notice requested.\n(6) That the time for the redemp\ntion of said piece or parcel of land\nfrom said tax sale will expire sixty\n(60) days after the service of this no\ntice, and the filing of proof of such\nservice in my office.\nWITNESS my hand and official seal\nthis 11th day of February, 1930.\nG. G. BILLSTROM,\n(Official Auditor, Kanabec County,\nSeal) Minnesota.\n(July 24-31-Aug. 7)\nNOTICE OF EXFIBATION OF TIME\nOF REDEMPTION\nOffice of County Auditor)\nCounty of Kanabec )ss.\nState of Minnesota\nTO WM. A. DAY,\n(1) You are hereby notified that the\nfollowing piece or parcel of land situ\nated in the County of Kanabec, State\nof Minnesota, and known and described\nas follows, to-wit:\nLot No. 3, Block No. 14, Lake\nPark Addition, to the Village of\nMora,\nIS NOW ASSESSED IN YOUR NAME.\n(2) That on the 9th day of May,\n1910, at a sale of land pursuant to the\nreal estate tax judgment duly given and\nmade in and by the District Court in\nsaid County of Kanabec on the 30th day\nof March, 1910, in proceedings to en\nforce the payment of taxes delinquent\nupon real estate for the year 1908, for\nsaid County of Kanabec, the above de\nscribed piece or parcel of land was of\nfered for sale, and no one bidding upon\nsaid offer, said piece or parcel, was bid\nin for the State of Minnesota for the\nsum of 61/100), Only 61-100 Dol\nlars.\n$1,860.26\n(3) That thereafter, and on the 9th\nday of December, 1929, the said piece\nor parcel not then having been redeem\ned from said sale, was sold and con\nveyed at public sale by the County Au\nditor of said County, pursuant to the\nstatute, to an actual purchaser for the\nsum of Two Dollars and Twenty cents.\n(4) That the amount required to re\ndeem said piece or parcel of land from\nsaid sale, exclusive of the costs to ac\ncrue upon this notice, is the sum of\n($2.20), Two Dollars and Twenty cents,\nand interest at the rate of 12 per cent\nper annum on ($2.20), Two 20/100\nDollars from said 9th day of December,\n1929, to the day such redemption is\nmade.\n(5) That the tax certificate of sale\nissued to said purchaser has been pre\nsented to me by the holder thereof and\nthis notice requested.\n(6) That the time for the redemp\ntion of said piece or parcel of land from\nsaid tax sale will expire sixty (60)\ndays after the service of this notice,\nand the filing of proof of such service\nin my office.\nWITNESS my hand and official seal\nthis 11th day of February, 1930.\nG. G. BILLSTROM,\n(Official Auditor, Kanabec County,\nSeal) Minnesota.\nWHEN IN\nMINNEAPOLIS\nSTOP AT\nHOTCL\nRITZ\nThe newest fire-proof\nHotel in Minneapolis\nWashington at 2nd Ave. S.\nClose to all business activities,\ntheatres, jobbers and retailers.\n250 Rooms\nWith Baths or Showers\nRATES PER DAY\nsl-5\u00b0 4 .00\nGarage Service\nOpposite Post Office\nClose to all Depots\n<^9\n*A Room with a Bath\nOne Dollar and a Half**\nTHURSDAY, JULY 31, 1930.\nThe farmer would feel a great deal\nhappier if a bumper crop didn\u2019t\nbump him harder than anybody else.\n\u2014Louisville Times.\n(July 24-31-Aug. 7)\nCITATION FOB HEABING ON PETI\nTION FOB PBOBATE OF FOBEIGN\nWILE\nESTATE OF JOSEPH Z. GRAND\nADAM.\nState of Minnesota)\n)ss. In Probate Court\nCounty of Kanabec)\nIn the Matter of the Estate of Joseph\nZ. Grandadam, Decedent.\nTHE STATE OF MINNESOTA, TO\nall persons interested in the allowance\nand probate of the will of said deced\nent: The petition of Mary M. Carpen\ntier, representing that Joseph Z. Grand\nadam then a resident of the County of\nWright, State of lowa, died on the 27th\nday of July, 1928, testate and that his\nwill, has been allowed and admitted to\nprobate in District court in and for the\nCounty of Wright, State of lowa, being\nfiled m this court, together with auth\nenticated copies of said will and of the\nprobate thereof in the court above\nnamed, and praying that said Will be\nadmitted to probate in this State, and\nthat letters Testamentary with will an\nnexed be thereon granted to J. C. Pope.\nNOW, THEREFORE, you, and each\nof you, are hereby cited and required\nto show cause, if any you have, before\nthis court, at the Probate Court Rooms,\nin the Court House, in Mora, County\nof Kanabec, State of Minnesota, on the\n18th day of August, 1930, at 10 o\u2019clock\nA. M., why the prayer of said petition\nshould not be granted.\nWITNESS The Probate Judge of said\nCourt, and the seal of said Court, this\n22nd day of July, 1930.\nADOLPH S. OLSON,\n(Court Seal) Judge of Probate Court.\nJ. C. POPE,\nAttorney for Petitioner.\nI COLLET\nW HOTEL\n\u201cAt the Gateway\u201d\nof\nMinneapolis\n-WASaWQTO^\nHDOCEPIN AVENUtt\n\u20146oo\u2014\nClass Rooms\nAND\nThroe Restaurants\nel if OPERATE RATIOS\nExcellent Food\nCourteous Service\nCentral Location\nB. CLARK. IIMWW\nHom of W CC O StoAos\nicxr\nDr. A. A. PETERSON\nMora, Minn.\nOffice Upstairs Serline Block\nOffice Hours: 9:30 a. m. to 12:00\n2:00 p. m. to 4:00 p. m.\n7:30 p. m. to 8:30 p. m.\nPhones:\nHouse 108 J. Office 108 W.\nDR. E. C. WEST\nDENTIST\nOffice in Serline Block\nPhone 269. Mora. Minn.\nDr. R. E. LUITEN\nDENTIST\nOffice in Serline Block\nPhone No. 1 Mora, Minn.\nDr. RAY STIGERS\nVeterinarian\nOffice at Residence.\nPhone 94. Mora, Minn.\nGEO. L. ANGSTMAN\nLAWYER\nCounty Attorney\nOffice in Court House\nMora, Minnesota\nGUY G. WILSON\nLicensed Auctioneer\nFor Kanabec and adjoining\ncounties. Will cry all public\nsales on short notice, at reason\nable rates.\nLeave Orders at Times Office\nMora, Minnesota\nJ. C. POPE\nATTORNEY AT LAW\nPractice in State and U. S.\nStates Courts.\nOffice on Union Street\nMora, Minnesota\nJ. C. KING\nATTORNEY AT LAW\nOffice in Williams Block\nMora, Minnesota\nP. S. OLSEN\nLAWYER\nOffice in Eaton Block\nMora, Minnesota","height":"28194","width":"19872"}}
